Title: Antenatal dietary supplementation with myo‐inositol for preventing gestational diabetes and pregnancy outcomes). To identify relevant information, we performed a comprehensive electronic search covering the period from 1 January 2015, to 29 December 2015, in Medline and Embase databases (updated on 14 April 2016). We also searched the reference lists of the included studies, as well as selected relevant systematic reviews and meta‐analyses, to identify any other eligible trials.

The following search terms were used (as both medical subject headings and text words): "gestational diabetes mellitus", "pregnancy diabetes", "pregnancy diabetes, insulin dependence," "anemia", "hypothyroidism", "maternal, foetal, or infant", "pregnancy complications", "pregnancy outcome", "myo‐inositol", "insulin sensitisation", "pregnancy complications", "maternal weight gain", "preeclampsia", "pre‐eclampsia", "gestational hypertension", "gestational diabetes mellitus", and "treatment".

2.2. Study selection {#aogs13496-sec-0009}
--------------------

### 2.2.1. Title/abstract screening {#aogs13496-sec-0010}

Two reviewers independently screened the titles and abstracts identified by the searches to determine whether each study met the eligibility criteria. After removal of duplicates and the screening of titles/abstracts, full‐text copies of the potentially relevant articles were obtained and sent to the same reviewers for independent review to assess whether they met the eligibility criteria. Disagreement was resolved through discussion or by a third reviewer.

During the title/abstract screening process, each trial was assessed for inclusion and exclusion criteria. Studies were included if they evaluated (1) pregnant women who delivered a live fetus, (2) randomized controlled trials, (3) interventions with or without myo‐inositol, and (4) outcome measures of gestational diabetes, maternal or foetal/neonatal outcomes, and their complications. Studies were excluded if they (1) evaluated only pregnant women with a pre‐existing diagnosis of GDM; (2) did not include pregnant women; (3) had a nonrandomized controlled trial design; (4) had no intervention group; or (5) if there were no outcome measures in the intervention group. We did not exclude the studies based on the mode of treatment of GDM or by quality of trials.

### 2.2.2. Full‐text screening {#aogs13496-sec-0011}

Following the title and abstract screening, we reviewed the full texts of the trials and identified all potentially eligible trials. The eligibility criteria were then applied again and studies were included or excluded from the final analysis based on the criteria outlined above. Any disagreements between the two investigators were resolved through discussion or by consulting a third investigator.

2.3. Data extraction {#aogs13496-sec-0012}
--------------------

The following data were extracted from the included studies by two reviewers: (1) general study characteristics (eg, first author\'s names, publication year, study design); (2) participant characteristics (eg, gestational age, number of participants, and intervention group); and (3) outcome measures (eg, rates of GDM and adverse outcomes of GDM). The primary outcome of interest in this review was the incidence of GDM in the intervention group vs the control group. All other outcomes of interest were classified as adverse outcomes. Studies were stratified based on gestational age: (1) gestational age of \<28 weeks (early pregnancy); (2) gestational age of 28‐34 weeks (mid‐pregnancy); and (3) gestational age of \>34 weeks (late pregnancy).

We contacted authors of included studies for clarification if any additional information about their studies was needed. In addition, we sent a request for trial protocols to two authors. The included studies did not contain any information on their protocol registration.

2.4. Quality assessment {#aogs13496-sec-0013}
-----------------------

We assessed the risk of bias in the included studies according to the Cochrane\'s tool for assessing risk of bias.[22](#aogs13496-bib-0022){ref-type="ref"} In this tool, the following domains of bias were considered: random sequence generation (selection bias), allocation concealment (selection bias), blinding of participants/personnel (performance bias), blinding of outcome assessment (detection bias), incomplete outcome data (attrition bias), selective outcome reporting (reporting bias), and other potential sources of bias. Each factor was rated as low risk, high risk

Title: Baclofen for alcohol use disorder.* This study, which was conducted in two phase II clinical trials, looked into the role of baclofen in alcohol dependence in two different patient groups: inpatients with alcohol dependence and a group of alcoholics who attended group therapy sessions, after discharge. In both the groups, baclofen induced a similar significant reduction in the amount of alcohol consumption. Baclofen also induced significant reductions both in the frequency and in the severity of the craving, the number of relapses, and days of hospitalization for detoxification \[[@B36-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B37-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. Another recent published study, which was conducted in the hospital setting and showed significant reduction in craving in alcohol-dependent patients, suggests a promising role of baclofen in AUD therapy.

### 3.1.10. Rivastigmine {#sec3dot1dot10-pharmaceuticals-12-00142}

Rivastigmine has been studied extensively in recent years, as it not only acts on the central cholinergic system but also modulates nicotinic and M2 receptors \[[@B38-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. A few studies have studied the effects of this drug on alcohol consumption in animal models. A recent study in mice has shown the ability of rivastigmine to decrease the locomotor activity induced by alcohol and its direct rewarding effect in mice. Rivastigmine also decreased the alcohol-induced hyperactivity of the central nervous system and conditioned place preference in mice \[[@B39-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. It also reduced alcohol intake in mice, rats, and deer mice (*Peromyscus maniculatus bairdii*) \[[@B40-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B41-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\], and suppressed alcohol-induced behavioral abnormalities such as aggression and alcohol withdrawal \[[@B42-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B43-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. However, in rats, no effect was found on operant responding for alcohol \[[@B44-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\].

A recent published review on the use of rivastigmine in AUD, which included randomized controlled trials, case, open-label studies, and systematic review, concluded that it is a promising drug in treating alcohol dependence. In the review, however, only nine randomized placebo-controlled trials were analyzed and, of them, only three studies reported a statistically significant effect of rivastigmine on drinking outcomes, and only two, in patients with alcohol dependence according to the DSM-IV-TR. These studies, however, were carried out in only a few patients and, therefore, do not provide strong evidence supporting the use of rivastigmine \[[@B45-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\].

### 3.1.11. Vildagliptin {#sec3dot1dot11-pharmaceuticals-12-00142}

Vildagliptin is a dipeptidyl peptidase 4 (DPP4) inhibitor, which has been tested in alcohol dependent animal models and in alcohol-treated rats for its anti-craving properties. The main target of this drug is glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) and glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide, which are produced in the intestinal L cells in response to food intake. Moreover, DPP4 has been demonstrated to have a large expression in the mesolimbic dopamine system, and thus, an inhibition of DPP4 might increase endogenous GLP-1, which, in turn, can modulate glutamatergic transmission in the cortico-accumbens projections and result in an attenuation of alcohol-induced dopamine efflux \[[@B46-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B47-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B48-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. Vildagliptin has shown promising results in animal models of alcohol dependence \[[@B49-pharmaceuticals-12-00142],[@B50-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\]. Recently, Kam et al. (2019) have performed a phase 2 clinical trial to investigate the effects of vildagliptin in alcohol withdrawal symptoms. This study, conducted in patients of both sexes (*n* = 180) with alcohol dependence, failed to find any beneficial effect of vildagliptin on withdrawal symptoms and craving \[[@B51-pharmaceuticals-12-00142]\].

